and the subsequent death of her father threw her into a position unprecedented in the Gothic world: a regent mother who assumed control of the government.During her regency, Amalasuintha clashed with a conservative Gothic aristocracy who resisted her leadership, garnered support among her Roman and pro-Roman subjects, defended Italy from the ambitions of other kings, and negotiated the expansionistic designs of Justinian and Theodora. When her son died unexpectedly at a young age, she undertook her most dangerous political enterprise: forming an unmarried coregency with her cousin, Theodahad, whom she raised to the throne. His final betrayal would cost Amalasuintha her rule and her life.Vitiello argues that Amalasuintha's story reveals a key phase in the transformation of queenship in late antiquity and the early Middle Ages, a time in which royal women slowly began exercising political power. Assessing the ancient sources for Amalasuintha's biography, Cassiodorus, Procopius, Gregory of Tours, and Jordanes, Vitiello demonstrates the ways in which her life and public image show the influence of late Roman and Byzantine imperial models on the formation of female political power in the post-Roman world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Jul 2018) 4aAncient Studies. 4aClassics. 4aHistory. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook package 2017-2019z978311065989408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065747008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2018z978311060663840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812294347423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812294347.jpg  a978-3-11-060663-8  Univ.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-